[4] Suspected, research

15 May 2015 Italy: 2nd Italian infected by Ebola virus illustrates rich-poor divide
http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2015-05/16/c_134243262.htm
["... the problem in curbing the spread of the disease. 'The infected nurse in Italy will have about 40 health professionals looking after him, to make sure he will recover,' Prof. Giovani Rezza of the Institute of Health said in an interview. "In the infected countries, a single health care worker must look after 40 infected people"]

14 May 2015 USA (Connecticut): Patient in Connecticut tests negative for Ebola
http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/05/14/us-ebola-usa-connecticut-idUSKBN0NY21A20150514

Non-governmental organizations
------------------------------
14 May 2015 African Union (AU): After Ebola, can Africa take lead in responding to health emergencies?
http://theglobalobservatory.org/2015/05/ebola-african-union-health/

15 May 2015 MSF: MSF reflects on Ebola outbreak
http://www.voanews.com/content/ebola-looking-back-15may15/2769127.html
[Medecines Sans Frontieres found that fear of Ebola was the biggest issue they had to overcome, especially when fear lead to denial of, or exposure to, infection.]

Research, vaccines, drugs
-------------------------
14 May 2015 Liberia: [July 2015, ahead-of-print publication]: Monitoring of Ebola Virus Makona Evolution through Establishment of Advanced Genomic Capability in Liberia
http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/21/7/15-0522_article
[The US Army Medical Research Institute of Infectious Diseases (USAMRIID) has established the 1st genomic surveillance capability in Liberia, enabling them to monitor genetic changes in the virus within one week of sample collection]

15 May 2015 Liberia: Ebola trial vaccine volunteers to be monitored
http://allafrica.com/stories/201505150401.html?viewall=1
[According to co-investigator Dr. Steven Kennedy, volunteers who participated in the vaccine trial will be monitored for life safety, adding there is a need to keep track of them into their various communities to ensure that they don't experience any problematic side effects. The Phase II study ended with 549 persons participating in the process, 16 percent of whom are female]

14 May 2015 Sierra Leone: Researchers map evolution of Ebola in Sierra Leone
http://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/science/researchers-map-evolution-of-ebola-in-sierra-leone/article7206533.ece
[Chinese researchers have detected increased genetic diversity in Ebola virus collected in Sierra Leone]

14 May 2015 USA: A retrospective and prospective analysis of the West African Ebola virus disease epidemic: Robust national health systems at the foundation and an empowered WHO at the apex [Lancet, Vol. 385, pp. 1902-1909, 2015]
http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2604976

14 May 2015 West Africa: Why did Liberia beat Ebola before Guinea or Sierra Leone?
http://allafrica.com/stories/201505141065.html?viewall=1
[According to the WHO, there were 4 factors: the leadership of President Shirleaf; health officials and their partners were quick to recognize the importance of community engagement; generous support from the international community, including financial, logistical, and human resources; and strong coordination of the international and national response were essential for success.]
http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2015/liberia-ends-ebola/en/

15 May 2015 USA: New study eases fear of airborne Ebola
http://www.dddmag.com/news/2015/05/new-study-eases-fear-airborne-ebola
[The research team looked at samples from patients and great apes collected during Ebola epidemics from 1976 through 2014. They discovered that most genetic changes are lost between epidemic waves and found little evidence to support the evolution of a more powerful or transmissible virus.]

15 May 2015 USA: FDA [US Food and Drug Administration] panel considers best approval process for Ebola vaccines
http://www.pharmacytoday.org/fda-panel-considers-best-approval-process-ebola-vaccines

Funding
-------
15 May 2015 Sierra Leone: Health minister wants World Bank Ebola money probe
http://allafrica.com/stories/201505150450.html?viewall=1
[The Minister of Health and Sanitation has disclosed that his ministry and the government of Sierra Leone are gravely concerned about the management of Ebola funds by non-governmental organizations, noting that Audit Service Sierra Leone had written an official letter to the World Bank for an explanation as to the management of Ebola funds which were directly under the supervision of the Bank and other non-governmental organizations]

